I now have a clear picture of the bug. Let me confirm the exact logic:

The bug is in `LinkReferences::visit(Reference& ope)` at line 2500-2504. When a macro parameter name (e.g., `D`) collides with a global rule name (also `D`), the code:
1. Correctly sets `found_param = true` and `ope.iarg_ = i` (marking it as a macro parameter)
2. But then **unconditionally** also sets `ope.rule_ = &rule` when the name exists in the grammar

Then in `Reference::parse` (line 2348), the check `if (rule_)` runs first — so when `D` appears inside the body of macro `B(D)`, it has both `iarg_` set (correct: parameter) and `rule_` set (wrong: global rule `D`). The `if (rule_)` branch wins, so it calls the global rule `D` (matching `'d'`) instead of the macro parameter (which should be `C`, matching `'c'`).

---

ROOT CAUSE: `peglib.h:2500-2504` — In `LinkReferences::visit`, when a reference name matches both a macro parameter and a global grammar rule, `ope.rule_` is set unconditionally even though the reference is a macro parameter. `Reference::parse` checks `rule_` first (line 2348), so the global rule takes priority over the macro parameter, causing the parameter to be silently ignored and the global same-named rule to be called instead.

LOCAL FIX: Add a guard so `ope.rule_` is only set when the reference is **not** a macro parameter:
```cpp
// Before (line 2500-2504):
if (grammar_.count(ope.name_)) {
    auto& rule = grammar_.at(ope.name_);
    ope.rule_ = &rule;
}

// After:
if (!found_param && grammar_.count(ope.name_)) {
    auto& rule = grammar_.at(ope.name_);
    ope.rule_ = &rule;
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Enforce a hygiene rule at grammar-validation time (in `ReferenceChecker`) that macro parameter names must not shadow any top-level grammar rule names — emit a compile-time error (or at minimum a warning) whenever a parameter identifier collides with a defined rule. This eliminates the entire class of silent shadowing bugs by making the ambiguity a parse-time error rather than leaving it to runtime precedence between `rule_` and `iarg_`, which is fragile and order-dependent.
